<br>
The stupid nodrop linings, and the 5% fail rate are things that do make the macro code longer and more complicated.  But not really _that_ bad.  Using a madeup macro language (here by called Ninen++Sharp &lt;G&gt;) here is how i'd do it.  Curser will physically move between separate XXX,YYY locations (so I can be lazy and not have to type/cut/paste out &quot;Move curser to XXX,YYY&quot; a billion times.)<br>
<br>
Start with 6 empty 10 slot bags.  Lets say were in a zone that has both clay vender, water vender, sketch vender, wheel, and kiln.  You have 1000plat on you, and your int/wis gear plus enough Cha for best prices on.  Start in front of the Clay Vender.<br>
<br>
&lt;begin macro1&gt;<br>
Rclick at XXX,YYY &lt;opens up clay vender&gt;<br>
Shiftclick at XXX,YYY &lt;buys stack of clay&gt;<br>
Click and drag from XXX,YYY to XXX,YYY &lt;makes sheets visable&gt;<br>
Shiftclick at XXX,YYY &lt;buys stack of firing sheets&gt;<br>
Move to XXX,YYY &lt;move to sketch vender&gt;<br>
Rclick at XXX,YYY &lt;opens up sketch vender&gt;<br>
Click and drag from XXX,YYY to XXX,YYY &lt;makes sketches visable&gt;<br>
Shiftclick at XXX,YYY &lt;buys stack of ceramic lining sketches&gt;<br>
Move to XXX,YYY &lt;move to water vender&gt;<br>
Rclick at XXX,YYY &lt;opens up water vender&gt;<br>
Shiftclick at XXX,YYY &lt;buys stack of water&gt;<br>
Click at XXX,YYY &lt;picks up bag with supplies from slot1&gt;<br>
Click at XXX,YYY &lt;swaps bag from slot1 with bag in slot5&gt;<br>
Click at XXX,YYY &lt;drops empty bag in slot1&gt;<br>
Move to XXX,YYY &lt;move to pottery wheel&gt;<br>
&lt;end macro1&gt;<br>
&lt;begin macro2&gt;<br>
Rclick at XXX,YYY &lt;opens up Wheel&gt;<br>
Rclick at XXX,YYY &lt;opens up slot5&gt;<br>
CtrlClick at XXX,YYY &lt;picks up one water&gt;<br>
Click at XXX,YYY &lt;drops water in wheel slot1&gt;<br>
CtrlClick at XXX,YYY &lt;picks up one clay&gt;<br>
Click at XXX,YYY &lt;drops clay in wheel slot2&gt;<br>
CtrlClick at XXX,YYY &lt;picks up one sketch&gt;<br>
Click at XXX,YYY &lt;drops clay in wheel slot3&gt;<br>
Click at XXX,YYY &lt;clicks combine&gt;<br>
Click at XXX,YYY &lt;clicks on Autoequip slot&gt;<br>
Alt-tab out to the macro program and Cut'N'paste the last 8 lines 19 times (for a total of 20 combines to get unfired linings filling bags in slot1 and 2)...<br>
&lt;end macro2&gt;<br>
<br>
Ok, i'm bored, you're bored, we're all bored for ice-bored! Or something. So after this you just do similar to the above to move to the kiln, and start firing the linings.  When you get to your 18th lining, or whatever the last successfull one you made out of your 20 attempts, eq will complain about bad recipies and having @#%$ on your cursor after hitting combine, but eh, woopty doo.  End the firing macro with a &quot;click on Autoequip, click on slot I put fireing sheet in, click on autoequip&quot; to clean out the kiln.  Manually move any extra sheets back to your supplies bag or just sell them.<br>
<br>
And bingo, you just turned 20 sketches/waters/clays into 15-18 linings.  Exchange the bags in slots 1 and 5.  Set up a new macro to buy your casserole supplies (clay, sketches, sheets and water).  Its been a while, I can't remember if large blocks stack or not.  If so, set the macro to buy 20 of them, if not, just do 10 (so you can keep all your storebaught supplies in the one bag for simplicity).  Exchange 1 and 5 back again (putting supplies in slot5 and empty bag in slot 1.  macro up the combines to casserole dishes (the completed dish, if successfull will fill in the empty slots left by used linings.)<br>
<br>
Bingo, you've through the use of one longass macro, or a bunch of smaller macros chained together, have tryed a run of 20ish casserole dishes.  Make a macro to sell everything in the bags in slot 1 and 2 (and 5, if you wish to spend a little more, but not end up with extra fireing sheets of 2 varieties).  Then repeat the whole thing agian, for the next set.<br>
<br>
I, personally and in my work environment, have always liked using alot of smaller macros chained together, rather than 1 longass one.  And using the above, run through the fictional Ninen++Sharp macro program, would allow you to make runs of 20 dishes with 1/50th the number of clicks you'd normally use.  And since you're only doing 20 combines at a time, you're looking at may'be 30ish seconds of &quot;macro time&quot;, leaving plenty to wave back at GMs, or chat with them or whatever.<br>
<br>
Anyways, this was entirely too long winded.<br>
<br>
Ninen of Saryrn<br>
